The paper deals with auctions and mechanism design, which are core topics in game theory and algorithmic game theory. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a new hierarchy over set functions, which is related to optimization and combinatorial algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also discusses the efficiency of auctions in the presence of complements, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence and machine learning, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category. The paper also analyzes the price of anarchy, which is a key concept in algorithmic game theory and economics, making cs.EC (Economics and Computation) a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses regret minimization algorithms, which are commonly used in machine learning and reinforcement learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category.
